25|$|During this era, Havasupai {{relations}} with other Native American tribes were generally mixed. Bonds and interactions with <b>the</b> <b>Hopi</b> tribe, whose reservation was in close proximity, were strong, as the two peoples did {{a great deal of}} trading with each other. <b>The</b> <b>Hopi</b> introduced crops such as the gourd and sunflower that would eventually become a staple of the Havasupai diet. Still, the Havasupai were not without enemies as they were consistently at odds with the Yavapai and the Southern Paiute, who would steal and destroy crops planted by the Havasupai.|$|E
